{"key":"processedPost-10665920","value":{"id":10665920,"first":10665613,"last":10665973,"when":1247455582,"utime":"07/13/09 06:26 AM","content":"The most common causes of dry grains are failure to turn down the stove once the PC reaches pressure.&nbsp; Every time the weight rattles, steam escapes from the PC AND from the jars.&nbsp; The second most common cause is lifting the weight at the end of the cycle to dump steam.&nbsp; This dries out the jars because they're still at 15 psi inside the jars, thus that steam escapes, taking the moisture with it.&nbsp; Always allow the PC to cool slowly and naturally.<br /><br />Positive pressure won't dry out your jars because there will be no air flowing into them.&nbsp; The pressure inside the jar and outside will be equal.&nbsp; If you're going to run positive pressure, get a magna-helic or build a simple manometer from plastic tubing, and don't operate at over 1\" W.G. or you're just wasting electricity for no additional benefit.<br />RR","title":"Re: My dry jars. The fault of my positive pressure growroom?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}